The paper proposes a methodology to transform a noncooperative game into a Stackelberg game to overcome the deficiency of Nash equilibria in multiuser networks. This involves analyzing the interactions among selfish users sharing a common transmission channel, which falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The paper also discusses the informational requirements for the Stackelberg game, which suggests a focus on networking and information theory (cs.NI, cs.IT). Additionally, the paper examines the effects of relaxation on performance, which could be related to machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.MA) or social and information networks (cs.SI).
